One path option is a damage path, which essentially does this you get an extra damage spell for a reasonable amount of mana cost that does about 2/3 of the dmg a DD spell of equal level will do. Only the path spell draws little to no aggro, this is its big advantage. <br>
<br>
The second path option is Mana. You are granted a mana spell which allows you to increase you total mana maximum and recharges some of your mana back. The advantage of this spell is while the casting cost is higher you gain more mana back then it costs to cast it and the recast time is 2 seconds. <br>
<br>
So here is a break down of the two options. <br>
The damage option from speaking to other wizards, because I didn’t take this option, is the worse of the two options to take from what I have learned and here is why. <br>
<br>
1. The low to nil aggro spells are nice in the beginning but after about level 30 the 2/3 dmg they do just isn't enough anymore and I rarely speak to a wizard that chose this path who actually uses them anymore because of low dmg. After about level 34 or so when you get a boost to about 800+ damage on spells, and Tanks have far better taunts, the aggro seems to become less of an issue and the low dmg the spells do just isn't worth it. <br>
Second you are given a staff (2 handed) instead of a wand (1 handed). This is key, because I have yet to see a staff with stats that are equal or better than stats given from two wands of equal level. <br>
So essentially you get screwed out of one slot which can add a lot of nice dex and int bonuses thus letting you max your primary pool stats faster. They do make these staves two a lot more dmg then wands, but no wizard worth anything is ever in the battle actually hitting a mob. So it is a wasted attribute on the already worthless 2 handed staff. <br>
<br>
The second option, Mana regen, seems to be the far better choice. And here is why: <br>
<br>
1. On top of the standard mana regen spells Harvest, gather power and influx, you get a fourth spell to use as well that has a recast time of 2 instead of recast time ranging from 45 seconds to 200 seconds. <br>
When you combine all of them, in a series like this, Mental boost (level 40 class spell), harvest, gather power, influx, and mental boost again. I can cycle and cast all of these spells within about 15 seconds and gain back about 1/3 to 1/2 of my total mana bar. All in about the time it will take a tank to finish of a mob, loot, wait for respawn and pull the next mob. This almost eliminates the need for me to drink. <br>
Again I say almost, I still have to drink to recharge my mana but it is a lot less often now with 4 mana regen spells. <br>
Second you are given a wand (1 handed) as reward instead of a Staff thus giving you an extra slot to have a stat boosting item. <br>
<br>
All in all it seems the mana path has a lot more benefits then the damage path. This is sad in a way as well, and needs to be balanced. Because if you gain this knowledge ahead of time and can make a more informed decision about your wizard before you burn hundreds of hours only to find out you picked a path you don’t like, and want to switch but don’t want to go out of your path because you wont get the big reward spell at 49. It kind of forces most all wizards to choose the same path due to the imbalance and thus there is less diversity among the wizard class. <br>
<br>
Hopefully this will be changed in the near future and balance will come to both paths making them equally desirable. <br>
<br>
Again the information I have presented to you is to help you make a more informed decision about the path you choose. I do not claim to have all the facts about both paths I only have information about the path I choose and information about the other path based on what many other wizards who chose that path have told me. <br>
<br>
In addition I have recently found out that if you take the Dmg line and stick with it till 49 you get a very nice damage spell at the end It does a whooping 1330+ dmg which is better the the standard dmg spell you are given, Ice comet. <br>
<br>
